  "text": "Goose erythrocytes were agglutinated by five strains of rabies virus grown in monolayer cell cultures at pH 6.4 and at 0 to 4 C. Hemagglutination was not affected by the cell type in which the virus was grown. Prerequisites for occurrence of hemagglutination are absence of hemagglutination inhibitors (such as those contained in bovine serum) and a relatively high virus concentration (> 105 plaqueforming units of virus per ml). \"Soluble\" hemagglutinin was not present in crude preparations of extracellular virus. Treatment of purified preparations of extracellular virus with Tween 80 and ether did not result in release of a \"soluble\" hemagglutinin. The Until recently, only three methods for the assay of rabies virus were available: titration of infectivity in animals, plaque assay in cell cultures [CITATION_1] , and complement fixation (CF). The latter method (24) measures both infectious virus and all noninfectious viral antigens. In 1968, Halonen et al. [CITATION_2] reported that rabies virus exhibits hemagglutinating activity (HA). This paper deals with the characterization and mechanism of this phenomenon.",
